07661nam a22009015i 9780812207910DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20162012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122079107 a10.9783/97808122079102doi  a(DE-B1597)469670  a(OCoLC)979578067  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a331.88097322304aThe Right and Labor in America :bPolitics, Ideology, and Imagination /ced. by Nelson Lichtenstein, Elizabeth Tandy Shermer. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (440 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Culture in Modern America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Entangled Histories: American Conservatism and the U.S. Labor Movement in the Twentieth and Twenty-First Centuries -- tPart I. The Conservative Search for Social Harmony -- tChapter 1: Unions, Modernity, and the Decline of American Economic Nationalism -- tChapter 2. The American Legion and Striking Workers During the Interwar Period -- tChapter 3. Democracy or Seduction? The Demonization of Scientific Management and the Deification of Human Relations -- tPart II. Region, Race, and Resistance to Organized Labor -- tChapter 4. Capital Flight, ‘“States’ Rights,” and the Anti-Labor Offensive After World War II -- tChapter 5. Orval Faubus and the Rise of Anti-Labor Populism in Northwestern Arkansas -- tChapter 6. “Is Freedom of the Individual Un-American?” Right-to-Work Campaigns and Anti-Union Conservatism, 1943–1958 -- tPart III. Appropriating the Language of Civil Rights -- tChapter 7. Singing “The Right-to-Work Blues”: The Politics of Race in the Campaign for “Voluntary Unionism” in Postwar California -- tChapter 8. Whose Rights? Litigating the Right to Work, 1940–1980 -- tChapter 9. “Such Power Spells Tyranny”: Business Opposition to Administrative Governance and the Transformation of Fair Employment Policy in Illinois, 1945–1964 -- tPart IV. The Specter of Union Power and Corruption -- tChapter 10. Pattern for Partnership: Putting Labor Racketeering on the Nation’s Agenda in the Late 1950s -- tChapter 11. “Compulsory Unionism”: Sylvester Petro and the Career of an Anti-Union Idea, 1957–1987 -- tChapter 12. Wal-Mart, John Tate, and Their Anti-Union America -- tChapter 13. “All Deals Are Off”: The Dunlop Commission and Employer Opposition to Labor Law Reform -- tChapter 14. Is Democracy in the Cards? A Democratic Defense of the Employee Free Choice Act -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe legislative attack on public sector unionism that gave rise to the uproar in Wisconsin and other union strongholds in 2011 was not just a reaction to the contemporary economic difficulties faced by the government. Rather, it was the result of a longstanding political and ideological hostility to the very idea of trade unionism put forward by a conservative movement whose roots go as far back as the Haymarket Riot of 1886. The controversy in Madison and other state capitals reveals that labor's status and power has always been at the core of American conservatism, today as well as a century ago.The Right and Labor in America explores the multifaceted history and range of conservative hostility toward unionism, opening the door to a fascinating set of individuals, movements, and institutions that help explain why, in much of the popular imagination, union leaders are always "bosses" and trade union organizers are nothing short of "thugs." The contributors to this volume explore conservative thought about unions, in particular the ideological impulses, rhetorical strategies, and political efforts that conservatives have deployed to challenge unions as a force in U.S. economic and political life over the century. Among the many contemporary books on American parties, personalities, and elections that try to explain why political disputes are so divisive, this collection of original and innovative essays is essential reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLabor unions--United States--History--20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aBruce, Kyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Andrew Wender, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Tami J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGourse, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Sophia Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLichtenstein, Nelson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLichtenstein, Nelson, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLogan, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCartin, Joseph A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNehls, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNyland, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrr, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPierce, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchiller, Reuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShermer, Elizabeth Tandy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShermer, Elizabeth Tandy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVinel, Jean-Christian, econtributor.4ctb4